<p>Arizona ranks among the top three states nationally for solar energy potential, with most regions receiving between 5.5 to 6.2 peak sun hours daily. The Phoenix metropolitan area, home to over 4.8 million residents, enjoys some of the highest solar irradiance levels in the continental United States, with an average solar irradiance of 6.58 kWh/m¬≤/day. This exceptional solar resource means that a typical 6kW residential solar system in Arizona can generate between 9,000 to 11,000 kWh annually, compared to just 7,000-8,000 kWh in less sunny states like Pennsylvania or Washington.</p>

<p>The state's high altitude and low humidity levels contribute to optimal photovoltaic performance, as solar panels operate more efficiently in dry conditions. Arizona's consistent weather patterns, with minimal cloud cover during peak production hours, provide reliable and predictable energy generation throughout the year. Even during the hottest summer months when panel efficiency may decrease slightly due to extreme temperatures, the extended daylight hours and intense solar radiation ensure robust energy production that easily offsets seasonal variations.</p>

