<h2>HVAC Systems in Arizona</h2>
<h3>Climate Considerations</h3>
<p>Arizona's extreme desert climate presents unique challenges for HVAC systems, with summer temperatures in Phoenix and Tucson regularly exceeding 115¬∞F and cooling degree days averaging over 4,000 annually. The intense heat creates enormous cooling demands from May through October, with peak electrical usage occurring during afternoon hours when temperatures soar and air conditioning systems work hardest. During these peak periods, HVAC systems can account for 60-70% of total home energy consumption, making efficient cooling systems essential for managing utility costs.</p>

<p>The dry desert climate, while challenging for cooling, offers some advantages for HVAC system operation. Low humidity levels mean that air conditioning systems don't need to work as hard to remove moisture from the air, allowing them to focus primarily on temperature reduction. However, the extreme temperature differentials between outdoor and indoor conditions - often 40-50¬∞F or more - place significant stress on HVAC equipment, requiring robust systems designed for continuous operation in harsh conditions. Proper system sizing becomes critical, as undersized units will struggle to maintain comfort while oversized systems may short-cycle and provide poor humidity control during milder weather.</p>

